Stedor Enters., Ltd. v. Armtex, Inc.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 947 F.2d 727, 729\u8211\'3f32 (4th Cir.1991)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Chrysler\rquote s request for arbitration is embedded because the issue of arbitrability arises here in the context of a claim for relief (brought by Seacoast) that goes beyond a determination of the arbitrability of the dispute. It does not matter that all of the substantive claims in the suit\u8212\'3fthe \u8220\'3fother relief sought\u8221\'3f\u8212\'3fare would-be subjects of the arbitration. 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1994030943&pubNum=506&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_506_96&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)#co_pp_sp_506_96" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Gammaro v. Thorp Consumer Discount Co.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 15 F.3d 93, 96 (8th Cir.1994)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (holding that, even when the pending suit is limited to arbitrable claims, the order compelling arbitration is embedded); 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1993172627&pubNum=506&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_506_318&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)#co_pp_sp_506_318" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Humphrey,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 4 F.3d at 318
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (same).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F51998104702_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[5]
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B51998104702_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B51998104702_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 However, that arbitrability was an embedded issue does not by itself answer the jurisdictional question. In most embedded proceedings in which the district court\rquote s decision favors arbitration, the district court, pursuant to 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000546&cite=9USCAS3&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=LQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 3
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, stays the action pending arbitration. Here, by contrast, although the district court granted Chrysler\rquote s motion to compel arbitration, it entered an order dismissing, rather than staying, the proceedings. We must address, then, whether a dismissal without prejudice in deference to arbitration in the context of an embedded proceeding is an appealable (that is, final) decision.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This circuit has not addressed this question before, and other circuits have been divided on the issue. As the Seventh Circuit outlined recently in 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1998072626&pubNum=506&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Napleton v. General Motors Corp.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 138 F.3d 1209 (7th Cir.1998)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, some circuits have determined that an order of dismissal accompanying an order favoring arbitration is appealable as a final decision, even if the proceeding is embedded, 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
see 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1995246514&pubNum=506&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_506_797&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)#co_pp_sp_506_797" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Armijo v. Prudential Ins. Co. of Am.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 72 F.3d 793, 797 (10th Cir.1995)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (finding jurisdiction when, in an embedded proceeding, the district court had ordered arbitration and dismissed action, on the basis that the moving party had requested that the action be dismissed, not stayed, pending arbitration); 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1991208242&pubNum=350&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_350_46&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)#co_pp_sp_350_46" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Nationwide Ins. Co. of Columbus, Ohio v. Patterson,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 953 F.2d 44, 46 (3d Cir.1991)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (finding jurisdiction to review an arbitration order on the basis that \u8220\'3fthe district court\rquote s dismissal of [the] action plainly signifies that th[e] arbitration is not a part of any ongoing proceeding\u8221\'3f); 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
see also 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1990170666&pubNum=350&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_350_1276&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)#co_pp_sp_350_1276" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Arnold v. Arnold Corp.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 920 F.2d 1269, 1276 (6th Cir.1990)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (discerning in the FAA\rquote s legislative history an intention to abrogate the distinction between embedded and independent proceedings and to \u8220\'3fallow [ ] appeals from final decisions affecting arbitration whether or not they direct or refuse to direct arbitration,\u8221\'3f and, correspondingly, finding jurisdiction to review an arbitration order in which the proceedings had been dismissed), while other circuits have focused on the distinction between embedded and independent proceedings to determine whether jurisdiction exists over an appeal from a dismissal of an order favoring arbitration, 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
see 
}
}
