{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 panel followed the latter approach, concluding that \u8220\'3fit is the nature of the underlying action, not the style of the district court\rquote s decision requiring arbitration, that determines whether we have jurisdiction over appeals from decisions granting arbitration.\u8221\'3f 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1998072626&pubNum=506&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_506_1212&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)#co_pp_sp_506_1212" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
138 F.3d at 1212.
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 We do likewise and hold that we lack jurisdiction under the FAA to review whether the court\rquote s order compelling arbitration was proper. Such a result avoids elevating form over substance and promotes both the pro-arbitration purposes of the FAA and the institutional goal of avoiding piecemeal appeals and systemic delays. 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1998072626&originatingDoc=Ic8e70d6f944511d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 at 1212\u8211\'3f15.
}}}
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Accordingly, Seacoast\rquote s appeal is dismissed for want of appellate jurisdiction.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
